<section xml:id="sec-sum-and-difference-identities" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Sum and Difference Identities</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      The sum identities say that if you know about two angles <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m>, you can also find sine (or cosine, or tangent) of the two angles added together <m>\alpha + \beta</m>. The difference identities do the same for the difference (subtraction) <m>\alpha - \beta</m>.
    </p>
    
    <md>
      <mrow>
        \boxed{
          \begin{aligned}
          \sin{(\alpha + \beta)} &amp; = \sin{\alpha}\cos{\beta} + \cos{\alpha}\sin{\beta} \\
          \sin{(\alpha - \beta)} &amp; = \sin{\alpha}\cos{\beta} - \cos{\alpha}\sin{\beta} \\
          \cos{(\alpha + \beta)} &amp; = \cos{\alpha}\cos{\beta} - \sin{\alpha}\sin{\beta} \\
          \cos{(\alpha - \beta)} &amp; = \cos{\alpha}\cos{\beta} + \sin{\alpha}\sin{\beta} \\
          \tan{(\alpha + \beta)} &amp; = \frac{\tan{\alpha} + \tan{\beta}}{1 - \tan{\alpha}\tan{\beta}} \\
          \tan{(\alpha - \beta)} &amp; = \frac{\tan{\alpha} - \tan{\beta}}{1 + \tan{\alpha}\tan{\beta}}
          \end{aligned}
        }
      </mrow>
    </md>
    
    <p>
      These identities are maybe the most challenging to remember at first, so definitely keep them available when practicing.
    </p>
    <p>
      The 6 identities can be written more concisely as,
    </p>
    
    <md>
      <mrow>
        \boxed{\begin{array}{l}
        \sin{(\alpha \pm \beta)} = \sin{\alpha} \cos{\beta} \pm \cos{\alpha} \sin{\beta} \\[6pt]
        \cos{(\alpha \pm \beta)} = \cos{\alpha} \cos{\beta} \mp \sin{\alpha} \sin{\beta} \\[4pt]
        \tan{(\alpha \pm \beta)} = \dfrac{\tan{\alpha} \pm \tan{\beta}}{1 \mp \tan{\alpha} \tan{\beta}}
        \end{array}}
      </mrow>
    </md>
    
    <p>
      Notice that for cosine and tangent, the left has <m>\pm</m> while the right has a <m>\mp</m> sign, which means that <m>+</m> on the left goes with <m>-</m> on the right, and <m>-</m> on the left goes with <m>+</m> on the right.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-finding-exact-values-examples">
    <title>Finding Exact Values Examples</title>
    <p>
      The sum and difference identities can be used to find trigonometric ratios (like sine, cosine, and tangent) for several angles not typically found on the unit circle (i.e. not just <m>0, \pi/6, \pi/4, \pi/3, \pi/2</m> and their multiples).
    </p>
    
    <example>
      <title>Find Cosine of <m>\ang{105}</m></title>
      <p>
        Find <m>\cos{\ang{105}}</m>. We can calculate this, because <m>\ang{105} = \ang{60} + \ang{45}</m> is the sum of two special angles (which we know about). Then, the sum identity for cosine says,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\cos{\ang{105}} \amp = \cos{(\ang{60} + \ang{45})}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \cos{\ang{60}}\cos{\ang{45}} - \sin{\ang{60}}\sin{\ang{45}}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        This answer is correct, however we can continue to simplify the result into one fraction,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{4} - \frac{\sqrt{6}}{4}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{\sqrt{2} - \sqrt{6}}{4}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Therefore, <m>\cos{\ang{105}} = \frac{\sqrt{2} - \sqrt{6}}{4}</m>.
      </p>
    </example>
    
    <example>
      <title>Find Tangent of <m>\frac{5\pi}{12}</m></title>
      <p>
        Find <m>\tan{\brac{\frac{5\pi}{12}}}</m>. Here, after some trial and error, <m>\frac{5\pi}{12} = \frac{\pi}{4} + \frac{\pi}{6}</m>. Then,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\tan{\brac{\frac{5\pi}{12}}} \amp = \tan{\brac{\frac{\pi}{4} + \frac{\pi}{6}}}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{\tan{\frac{\pi}{4}} + \tan{\frac{\pi}{6}}}{1 - \tan{\frac{\pi}{4}}\tan{\frac{\pi}{6}}}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1 + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}}{1 - 1 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1 + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}}{1 - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        This answer is correct, however we can continue to simplify the result,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{3 + \sqrt{3}}{3 - \sqrt{3}} \amp\amp \text{multiplying numerator and denominator by 3}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        This is a solid final answer. However, some instructors will expect that you rationalize the denominator to fully simplify,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{3 + \sqrt{3}}{3 - \sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{3 + \sqrt{3}}{3 + \sqrt{3}} \amp\amp \text{multiplying numerator and denominator by $3 + \sqrt{3}$}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{3 + 2\sqrt{3} + 1}{2}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{4 + 2\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 2 + \sqrt{3}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Therefore, <m>\tan{\brac{\frac{5\pi}{12}}} = 2 + \sqrt{3}</m>.
      </p>
    </example>
    
    <p>
      This works for any angle which can be written as the sum of two special angles (or the difference of two special angles). Here are some of the common ones.
    </p>
    
    <ul>
      <li><m>\ang{15} = \ang{45} - \ang{30} = \ang{60} - \ang{45}</m></li>
      <li><m>\ang{75} = \ang{45} + \ang{30}</m></li>
      <li><m>\ang{105} = \ang{60} + \ang{45}</m></li>
      <li><m>\ang{165} = \ang{120} + \ang{45}</m></li>
    </ul>
    
    <p>
      Notice that there is often more than one way to write it (but maybe there is one easier way). For example, <m>\ang{105} = \ang{60} + \ang{45}</m>, but also <m>\ang{105} = \ang{150} - \ang{45}</m>. Also, in radians,
    </p>
    
    <ul>
      <li><m>\frac{\pi}{12} = \frac{\pi}{4} - \frac{\pi}{6} = \frac{\pi}{3} - \frac{\pi}{4}</m></li>
      <li><m>\frac{5\pi}{12} = \frac{\pi}{4} + \frac{\pi}{6}</m></li>
      <li><m>\frac{7\pi}{12} = \frac{\pi}{3} + \frac{\pi}{4}</m></li>
      <li><m>\frac{11\pi}{12} = \frac{2\pi}{3} + \frac{\pi}{4}</m></li>
    </ul>
    
    <project>
      <title>Evaluate Exact Trigonometric Ratios</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Evaluate each trigonometric ratio exactly, and simplify your answer.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\sin{\ang{15}}</m></statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\cos{\brac{\frac{5\pi}{12}}}</m></statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\tan{\ang{105}}</m></statement>
        <answer><p><m>\frac{\sqrt{3}+1}{1-\sqrt{3}}</m> (or rationalized <m>-2 - \sqrt{3}</m>)</p></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\sin 105^\circ</m></statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\sin{\brac{\frac{7\pi}{12}}}</m></statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\tan{\ang{15}}</m></statement>
        <answer><p><m>\frac{3-\sqrt{3}}{3+\sqrt{3}}</m> (or rationalized, <m>2 - \sqrt{3}</m>)</p></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\cos{\ang{285}}</m></statement>
        <hint><p><m>\ang{285} = \ang{240} + \ang{45}</m> is one combination.</p></hint>
        <answer><m>\frac{\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\sin{\frac{23\pi}{12}}</m></statement>
        <hint><p><m>\frac{23\pi}{12} = \frac{5\pi}{3} + \frac{\pi}{4}</m> is one combination.</p></hint>
        <answer><m>\frac{\sqrt{2} - \sqrt{6}}{4}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\tan{\brac{-\frac{5\pi}{12}}}</m></statement>
        <hint><p><m>-\frac{5\pi}{12} = -\frac{\pi}{4} - \frac{\pi}{6}</m> is one combination.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\frac{-\sqrt{3}-3}{3-\sqrt{3}}</m> or <m>-2-\sqrt{3}</m></p></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\cot{\brac{\frac{11\pi}{12}}}</m></statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\sec{\brac{\frac{19\pi}{12}}}</m></statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\csc{(-\ang{105})}</m></statement>
      </task>
    </project>
    
    <remark>
      <p>
        In fact, there are only a relatively limited number of questions of this type that your teacher can give you. Here are pretty much all of them summarized in a table (between <m>\ang{0}</m> and <m>\ang{360}</m>),
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \begin{array}{c|c|c|c|c}
          \text{Angle (degrees)} &amp; \text{Angle (radians)} &amp; \text{Sine} &amp; \text{Cosine} &amp; \text{Tangent} \\
          \hline
          \ang{15} &amp; \frac{\pi}{12} &amp; \frac{\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; \frac{\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; 2 - \sqrt{3} \\[4pt]
          \ang{75} &amp; \frac{5\pi}{12} &amp; \frac{\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; \frac{\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; 2 + \sqrt{3} \\[4pt]
          \ang{105} &amp; \frac{7\pi}{12} &amp; \frac{\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; \frac{-\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; -2 - \sqrt{3} \\[4pt]
          \ang{165} &amp; \frac{11\pi}{12} &amp; \frac{\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; \frac{-\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; -2 + \sqrt{3} \\[4pt]
          \ang{195} &amp; \frac{13\pi}{12} &amp; \frac{-\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; \frac{-\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; 2 - \sqrt{3} \\[4pt]
          \ang{255} &amp; \frac{17\pi}{12} &amp; \frac{-\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; \frac{-\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; 2 + \sqrt{3} \\[4pt]
          \ang{285} &amp; \frac{19\pi}{12} &amp; \frac{-\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; \frac{\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; -2 - \sqrt{3} \\[4pt]
          \ang{345} &amp; \frac{23\pi}{12} &amp; \frac{-\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; \frac{\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4} &amp; -2 + \sqrt{3}
          \end{array}
        </mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Of course, you shouldn't memorize this table, but it's just to give you an idea of the question style you should expect, and the style of the final answer.
      </p>
    </remark>
    
    <p>
      My recommended calculator <url href="https://camerongeisler.com/calculator-guide-for-students-how-to-buy-a-calculator/">Casio fx-991ES Plus C 2nd edition</url> (or some other similar scientific calculators) can find exact values of these angles. For example, typing in <m>\sin{\brac{\frac{\pi}{12}}}</m> will output <m>\frac{\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}}{4}</m>. You can use this to at least check your work.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-exact-values-with-variable-angles">
    <title>Exact Values with Variable Angles</title>
    <example>
      <title>Cosine of Variable Angle Sum</title>
      <p>
        Let <m>\theta</m> be in quadrant III with <m>\cos{\theta}=-\frac{7}{8}</m>. Find <m>\cos\brac{\theta+\frac{\pi}{6}}</m> in exact value.
      </p>
      <p>
        To find <m>\cos\brac{\theta+\frac{\pi}{6}}</m>, use the sum identity,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\cos\brac{\theta+\frac{\pi}{6}} \amp = \cos\theta\cos\frac{\pi}{6}-\sin\theta\sin\frac{\pi}{6}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        We know <m>\cos{\frac{\pi}{6}}</m>, <m>\sin{\frac{\pi}{6}}</m>, and we are given <m>\cos{\theta}</m>, but we're also going to need to find <m>\sin{\theta}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        To do this, sketch the angle in standard position, which is in quadrant III. Since <m>\cos{\theta}=-\frac{7}{8}</m>, <m>x=-7</m> and <m>r=8</m>.
      </p>
      <image width="100%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5,&gt;=stealth]
          % axes
          \draw[-&gt;] (-9,0) -- (2,0) node[right] {};
          \draw[-&gt;] (0,-6) -- (0,2) node[above] {};
          
          % points
          \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
          \coordinate (A) at (-7,0);
          \coordinate (P) at (-7,-{sqrt(15)});
          
          % triangle
          \draw[thick] (O) -- (A) -- (P) -- cycle;
          
          % right angle marker
          \draw[thick] (-6.6,0) -- (-6.6,-0.4) -- (-7,-0.4);
          
          % labels
          \node[above] at (-3.5,0) {$-7$};
          \node[left] at (-7,-{sqrt(15)/2}) {$y$};
          \node[below right] at (-3.2,-{sqrt(15)/2}) {$8$};
          
          % point label
          \fill (P) circle (2pt);
          
          % standard-position angle with arrow
          \pgfmathsetmacro{\ang}{180+atan(sqrt(15)/7)}
          \draw[thick,-&gt;] (1.6,0) arc (0:\ang:1.6);
          
          % theta label placed in quadrant III
          \node at (-2.2,-0.6) {$\theta$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      <p>
        Then, find <m>y</m>, using <m>x^2+y^2=r^2</m>,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>(-7)^2+y^2\amp=8^2</mrow>
        <mrow>49+y^2\amp=64</mrow>
        <mrow>y^2\amp=15</mrow>
        <mrow>y\amp=\pm\sqrt{15}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Since <m>\theta</m> is in quadrant III, <m>y</m> must be negative, so <m>y=-\sqrt{15}</m>. Then, <m>\sin\theta=\frac{y}{r}=-\frac{\sqrt{15}}{8}</m>. Then,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\cos\brac{\theta+\frac{\pi}{6}}\amp=\cos\theta\cos\frac{\pi}{6}-\sin\theta\sin\frac{\pi}{6}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=\brac{-\frac{7}{8}}\brac{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}-\brac{-\frac{\sqrt{15}}{8}}\brac{\frac{1}{2}}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=-\frac{7\sqrt{3}}{16}+\frac{\sqrt{15}}{16}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=\boxed{\frac{\sqrt{15}-7\sqrt{3}}{16}}</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
    
    <p>
      In general, use a sum/difference identity to split into two angles.
    </p>
    
    <ul>
      <li>If it's a <em>special</em> angle, evaluate it directly.</li>
      <li>If it's a <em>variable</em> angle, sketch it, create a triangle with <m>x, y</m>, and <m>r</m>, and solve for the unknown side. Don't forget a negative sign if <m>x</m> or <m>y</m> is negative!</li>
    </ul>
    
    <project>
      <title>Find Exact Trigonometric Ratios</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find the desired trigonometric ratios in exact value, from the given information.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Let <m>\theta</m> be in quadrant IV with <m>\cos{\theta} = \frac{3}{5}</m>. Find <m>\cos{\brac{\theta + \frac{\pi}{3}}}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{3 + 4\sqrt{3}}{10}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Given that <m>\tan{x} = -1</m>, find <m>\tan{\brac{\frac{\pi}{3} + x}}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><p><m>\frac{\sqrt{3} - 1}{1 + \sqrt{3}}</m> or <m>2 - \sqrt{3}</m></p></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Given that <m>\sin{x}=\frac{4}{5}</m> and <m>x</m> is in quadrant I, find <m>\sin\brac{x+\frac{\pi}{6}}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{4\sqrt{3}+3}{10}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Given that <m>\tan{A} = -\frac{1}{4}</m> and <m>A</m> is in quadrant 2, and <m>\cos{B} = \frac{2}{5}</m> and <m>B</m> is in quadrant 4, find <m>\cos{(A - B)}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{-8-\sqrt{21}}{5\sqrt{17}}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Given that <m>\tan{x}=3</m>, find <m>\tan\brac{x+\frac{\pi}{4}}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><m>-2</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Given that <m>\cos{x}=\frac{12}{13}</m> and <m>x</m> is in quadrant I, find <m>\cos\brac{x+\frac{2\pi}{3}}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{-12-5\sqrt{3}}{26}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>If both <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are third quadrant angles and <m>\cos{B}=-\frac{12}{13}</m>, find <m>\sin\brac{A-B}</m> if <m>\sin{A}=-\frac{3}{5}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{16}{65}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Given that <m>\sin{\theta} = -\frac{4}{5}</m> and <m>\theta</m> is in quadrant III, find <m>\cos{\brac{\theta+\frac{\pi}{6}}}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{-3\sqrt{3}-4}{10}</m></answer>
      </task>
    </project>
    
    <project>
      <title>Find Exact Trigonometric Ratios 2</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find the desired trigonometric ratios in exact value, from the given information.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Given that <m>\tan{A}=\frac{5}{12}</m> and <m>A</m> is in quadrant III, and <m>\cos{B}=-\frac{3}{5}</m> and <m>B</m> is in quadrant II, find <m>\sin{(A-B)}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{63}{65}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Given that <m>\sin{A}=\frac{12}{13}</m> and <m>A</m> is in quadrant II, and <m>\sec{B}=\frac{5}{4}</m> and <m>B</m> is in quadrant IV, find <m>\cos\brac{A+B}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><m>\frac{16}{65}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Let <m>x, y</m> both be in quadrant I, with <m>\sin{x} = \frac{1}{5}, \cos{y} = \frac{2}{3}</m>. Find <m>\sin{(x+y)}</m> and <m>\cos{(x-y)}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><p><m>\sin{(x+y)} = \frac{2+2\sqrt{30}}{15}, \cos{(x-y)} = \frac{4\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{5}}{15}</m></p></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Given <m>A</m> is in quadrant 2 and <m>\sin{A}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}</m>, and <m>B</m> is in quadrant 3 and <m>\cos{B}=-\frac{5}{7}</m>, find <m>\cos{(A+B)}, \sin{(A-B)}</m>, and <m>\tan{(A+B)}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><p><m>\cos{(A+B)}=\frac{15+2\sqrt{6}}{7\sqrt{10}}</m> (or rationalized is <m>\frac{105\sqrt{10}+28\sqrt{15}}{490}</m>), <m>\sin{(A-B)}=\frac{-5-6\sqrt{6}}{7\sqrt{10}}</m> (or rationalized <m>\frac{-35\sqrt{10}-84\sqrt{15}}{490}</m>), <m>\tan{(A+B)} = \frac{-5+6\sqrt{6}}{15+2\sqrt{6}}</m></p></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>If <m>\sin{\alpha} = \frac{3}{5}</m> and <m>\sin{\beta} = -\frac{12}{13}</m>, with <m>\alpha</m> in quadrant II and <m>\beta</m> in quadrant IV, find <m>\sin{\brac{\alpha - \beta}}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><m>-\frac{33}{65}</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>Given <m>\alpha</m> is in quadrant II with <m>\sin{\alpha} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}</m> and <m>\beta</m> is in quadrant III with <m>\cos{\beta} = -\frac{5}{7}</m>, find <m>\sin{(\alpha + \beta)}, \cos{(\alpha + \beta)}</m>, and <m>\tan{(\alpha + \beta)}</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <answer><p><m>\sin{(\alpha + \beta)} = \frac{-5-6\sqrt{6}}{7\sqrt{10}}</m> (or rationalized <m>\frac{-5\sqrt{10} + 12\sqrt{15}}{70}</m>), <m>\cos{(\alpha + \beta)} = \frac{15 + 2\sqrt{6}}{7\sqrt{10}}</m> (or rationalized <m>\frac{15\sqrt{10} + 4\sqrt{15}}{70}</m>), <m>\tan{(\alpha + \beta)} = \frac{-5 + 6\sqrt{6}}{15 + 2\sqrt{6}}</m> (or rationalized <m>\frac{-147 + 100\sqrt{6}}{201}</m>)</p></answer>
      </task>
    </project>
    
    <p>
      Could also use inverse trig function and reference angle.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-simplifying-expressions-using-sum-and-difference-identities">
    <title>Simplifying Expressions Using Sum and Difference Identities</title>
    <project>
      <title>Simplifying Expressions</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Write each expression as a single trigonometric function.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\sin 28^\circ \cos 35^\circ + \cos 28^\circ \sin 35^\circ</m></statement>
        <answer><m>\sin 63^\circ</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\cos 10^\circ \cos 7^\circ - \sin 10^\circ \sin 7^\circ</m></statement>
        <answer><m>\cos 17^\circ</m></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><m>\sin \frac{\pi}{3} \cos \frac{\pi}{4} - \cos \frac{\pi}{3} \sin \frac{\pi}{4}</m></statement>
        <answer><m>\sin \brac{\frac{\pi}{12}}</m></answer>
      </task>
    </project>
    
    <project>
      <title>Simplify and Find Exact Values</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Simplify and find an exact value for each expression.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
